And he says to me,
oh, I think I'm just

00:07:52.814 --> 00:07:55.200
going to join
experimental physics.

00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:56.500
It's so much easier.

00:07:56.500 --> 00:07:58.190
And he says to me,
what do you guys do?

00:07:58.190 --> 00:08:02.132
Just bang around with
a hammer all day?

00:08:02.132 --> 00:08:04.760
And I was thinking,
God, I don't think

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:07.650
I've used a hammer
in my entire career

00:08:07.650 --> 00:08:08.907
as an experimental physicist.

00:08:08.907 --> 00:08:10.740
Is that really what you
guys think about us?

00:08:10.740 --> 00:08:13.120
That we're just like,
knock, knock, knock,

00:08:13.120 --> 00:08:14.450
like some sort of cave people?

00:08:18.497 --> 00:08:20.330
Every time I go into
the theory coffee room,

00:08:20.330 --> 00:08:23.430
it's like either a,
they're drinking coffee,

00:08:23.430 --> 00:08:26.750
or they're just kind of
writing something randomly

00:08:26.750 --> 00:08:32.520
on the board, or they're
reading magazines.

00:08:32.520 --> 00:08:34.240
Physics magazines,
I'll give them that.

00:08:38.615 --> 00:08:40.210
It does seem like
a life of leisure,

00:08:40.210 --> 00:08:41.679
actually, in some ways.

00:08:41.679 --> 00:08:43.437
It's kind of nice.

