mean the LHC took 20 years

00:12:38.908 --> 00:12:41.970
to build-- that in this waiting
period of these 20 years,

00:12:41.970 --> 00:12:45.810
there was really nothing
for us experimentalists

00:12:45.810 --> 00:12:47.370
to talk to the theorists about.

00:12:47.370 --> 00:12:49.520
So now I think, and
just in the last couple

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:51.490
of years, that has just
been revolutionized.

00:12:51.490 --> 00:12:53.850
We have terabytes of data.

00:12:53.850 --> 00:12:56.014
And so now we can
go and say, well

00:12:56.014 --> 00:12:58.180
this is what we found, or,
this isn't what we found.

00:12:58.180 --> 00:12:59.304
And what do you guys think?

00:12:59.304 --> 00:13:02.360
And there's a lot of
back and forth now.

00:13:02.360 --> 00:13:05.474
So I think the data sort
of has changed everything.

00:13:05.474 --> 00:13:07.640
MARK LEVINSON: I mean,
Martin and Mike actually both

00:13:07.640 --> 00:13:10.360
started in theory.

00:13:10.360 --> 00:13:13.300
You said you originally thought
you were interested in theory,

00:13:13.300 --> 00:13:17.200
and Mike, you've got a degree
in lattice gauge field, right?

00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:19.830
So you started in
theory, you've moved more

00:13:19.830 --> 00:13:21.990
towards the experimental side.

00:13:21.990 --> 00:13:23.880
Totally, in Martin's case.

00:13:23.880 --> 00:13:26.670
Did you make the right decision?

00:13:26.670 --> 00:13:31.520
Yes, I never regretted
this decision.

00:13:31.520 --> 00:13:33.570
I mean I started in theory.

00:13:33.570 --> 00:13:37.420
During my studies, I
spent a year or so deeply

00:13:37.420 --> 00:13:40.620
going into theory, and quantum
field theory, and so on.

00:13:40.620 --> 00:13:42.870
But I think it was just
natural [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:42.870 --> 00:13:45.110
for a particle
physicist afterwards.

00:13:45.110 --> 00:13:49.550
And then the choice
actually came.

00:13:49.550 --> 00:13:54.710
It was really CERN, I mean
this opportunity at CERN

00:13:54.710 --> 00:13:58.290
to work there, and to work
on these big experiments.

00:13:58.290 --> 00:14:00.829
And that happened to be
as an experimentalist.

00:14:00.829 --> 00:14:02.870
And that's why I signed
up as an experimentalist.

00:14:02.870 --> 00:14:03.560
But it's true.

00:14:03.560 --> 00:14:05.500
I mean, if this would have
been possible as a theorist,

00:14:05.500 --> 00:14:07.750
maybe I would have done a
totally different career.

00:14:07.750 --> 00:14:09.970
But anyway, for me
already at that point,

00:14:09.970 --> 00:14:13.090
it was clear that this
is a close collaboration.

00:14:13.090 --> 00:14:16.410
It's clear that one cannot
exist without the other.

00:14:16.410 --> 00:14:18.550
I mean, theory
without experiments,

00:14:18.550 --> 00:14:21.450
they would just develop
ideas, ideas, ideas,

00:14:21.450 --> 00:14:23.650
and they would diverge.

00:14:23.650 --> 00:14:26.730
And experimentalists
without theorists is a bit,

00:14:26.730 --> 00:14:31.350
you measure, but afterwards
you need an interpretation.

00:14:31.350 --> 00:14:35.234
And very often the measurement
itself can't tell you so much,

00:14:35.234 --> 00:14:36.900
but of course the
interpretation and how

00:14:36.900 --> 00:14:41.220
it fits into the theory, this
can explain you many things.

00:14:41.220 --> 00:14:43.380
And that's why
[INAUDIBLE] the LHC

00:14:43.380 --> 00:14:46.240
has impact on theories of
a big bang, on dark matter,

00:14:46.240 --> 00:14:47.060
and so on.

00:14:47.060 --> 00:14:48.893
This is because there's
this interpretation.

00:14:54.795 --> 00:14:56.420
SAVAS DIMOPOULOS:
Having theory develop

00:14:56.420 --> 00:14:58.730
before the experiments
actually happen

00:14:58.730 --> 00:15:01.770
is also very useful,
because that pinpoints

00:15:01.770 --> 00:15:04.020
the type of signatures
that experimentalists

00:15:04.020 --> 00:15:05.850
should look for.

00:15:05.850 --> 00:15:07.490
So it's very important.

00:15:07.490 --> 00:15:11.620
For example, the missing energy
signature of supersymmetry.

00:15:11.620 --> 00:15:13.170
I don't think it's
something that's

00:15:13.170 --> 00:15:15.440
obvious before you
have some theories that

00:15:15.440 --> 00:15:17.060
have this as a signature.

00:15:17.060 --> 00:15:18.340
And many other things.

00:15:18.340 --> 00:15:20.330
There is a famous
saying which says

00:15:20.330 --> 00:15:23.070
that, you have to
believe it to see it.

00:15:23.070 --> 00:15:25.420
You have to know ahead of
time what you're looking for

00:15:25.420 --> 00:15:28.050
to be able to see it.

00:15:28.050 --> 00:15:29.750
MARK LEVINSON: So
just going back

00:15:29.750 --> 00:15:32.350
to what people thought
they were going

00:15:32.350 --> 00:15:34.647
to see at the
beginning of this, I

00:15:34.647 --> 00:15:36.230
want to just look
at a couple of clips

00:15:36.230 --> 00:15:39.900
from some first interviews
of what people up here were

00:15:39.900 --> 00:15:43.230
thinking before it
actually turned on.

00:15:43.230 --> 00:15:45.014
Next clip.

00:15:45.014 --> 00:15:45.680
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:15:45.680 --> 00:15:48.450
-I think that we
are not in a crisis,

00:15:48.450 --> 00:15:52.830
but we are really in front of
a brick wall at the moment.

00:15:52.830 --> 00:15:56.680
We need, absolutely, some input
from experimental physics,

00:15:56.680 --> 00:16:01.200
from the collision
[INAUDIBLE] energy to move on.

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:03.830
-The worst possibility
is they discover

00:16:03.830 --> 00:16:06.010
the Higgs, nothing else.

00:16:06.010 --> 00:16:08.420
The new deep physics, dark
matter, supersymmetry,

00:16:08.420 --> 00:16:10.950
[INAUDIBLE], it's just
around the corner.

00:16:10.950 --> 00:16:13.207
But the LHC can't quite do it.

00:16:13.207 --> 00:16:15.290
And there's no way we're
going to convince anybody

00:16:15.290 --> 00:16:17.150
that it may be just
around the corner

00:16:17.150 --> 00:16:20.280
and it's worth
building other machine.

00:16:20.280 --> 00:16:24.130
So the field ends
because of that.

00:16:24.130 --> 00:16:25.510
A miscalculation.

00:16:25.510 --> 00:16:28.820
-You really begin to doubt
whether we can actually

00:16:28.820 --> 00:16:30.110
make this thing work.

00:16:30.110 --> 00:16:32.040
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:16:32.040 --> 00:16:33.880
MARK LEVINSON: So before.

00:16:33.880 --> 00:16:35.714
Where are we now, actually?

00:16:35.714 --> 00:16:36.505
What would you say?

00:16:38.810 --> 00:16:41.310
DAVID KAPLAN: Mine was the most
dramatic statement, I guess.

00:16:44.230 --> 00:16:45.730
Part of the motivation
for the movie

00:16:45.730 --> 00:16:49.340
was that when we
were up at night,

00:16:49.340 --> 00:16:51.480
I remember a conversation
with Nima at 3 o'clock

00:16:51.480 --> 00:16:54.400
in the morning at
CERN, thinking what

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:57.970
if we, as in theorists
thinking about physics

00:16:57.970 --> 00:17:01.810
at these energies, were
just on the wrong track.

00:17:01.810 --> 00:17:04.150
And that what would
be revealed would

00:17:04.150 --> 00:17:07.900
be that this program, at
least what we had dedicated

00:17:07.900 --> 00:17:11.240
our theoretical careers
to, or most of them,

00:17:11.240 --> 00:17:12.839
just happened to
be a wrong turn.

00:17:12.839 --> 00:17:14.680
And we had to go
some other direction.

00:17:14.680 --> 00:17:18.240
And that emotional
drama made me think

00:17:18.240 --> 00:17:20.920
somebody has got to record this.

00:17:20.920 --> 00:17:23.859
But that sort of drama
is a very human drama.

00:17:23.859 --> 00:17:25.250
It's a generational drama.

00:17:25.250 --> 00:17:32.700
It's that we people may
be affected negatively.

00:17:32.700 --> 00:17:35.670
You could look back and say, the
career didn't amount to much,

00:17:35.670 --> 00:17:39.370
because you didn't move in
the direction that brought us

00:17:39.370 --> 00:17:41.920
real progress, or at
least visible progress.

00:17:41.920 --> 00:17:44.630
But all those dead ends
are incredibly important

00:17:44.630 --> 00:17:45.330
regardless.

00:17:45.330 --> 00:17:46.990
We need to explore
all directions.

00:17:46.990 --> 00:17:48.690
And it doesn't matter--
this is actually

00:17:48.690 --> 00:17:52.830
something Nima said in
one of the interviews--

00:17:52.830 --> 00:17:54.750
it doesn't matter
what happens to you.

00:17:54.750 --> 00:17:55.990
It's not about you.

00:17:55.990 --> 00:17:58.110
It's not a personal thing.

00:17:58.110 --> 00:17:59.860
It's necessary
for so many people

00:17:59.860 --> 00:18:02.390
to be pushing in all directions,
because we don't really

00:18:02.390 --> 00:18:04.450
know what the big
answer will be,

00:18:04.450 --> 00:18:09.600
or the next piece of
information will be.

00:18:09.600 --> 00:18:11.970
Now the LHC has seen the Higgs.

00:18:11.970 --> 00:18:16.420
I felt much more emotional about
that than I expected to feel.

00:18:16.420 --> 00:18:19.850
Because one thing about the
distinction between theorists

00:18:19.850 --> 00:18:24.260
an experimentalists, theorists
might read a blog rumor

00:18:24.260 --> 00:18:26.460
and decide they know
what's going on.

00:18:26.460 --> 00:18:29.590
And experimentalists will
wait until the probability

00:18:29.590 --> 00:18:33.250
that they've seen an
accident is one in trillion,

00:18:33.250 --> 00:18:35.610
and then they'll say
publicly that they've

00:18:35.610 --> 00:18:37.100
discovered something.

00:18:37.100 --> 00:18:41.290
So that distinction
means that we're

00:18:41.290 --> 00:18:44.250
speculating in many
possible futures.

00:18:44.250 --> 00:18:47.000
And so when you hear me
talking a few years ago,

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.800
you're listening to
me speculating down

00:18:49.800 --> 00:18:52.010
one path or another.

00:18:52.010 --> 00:18:54.732
And I know Jerry,
who's here, told me

00:18:54.732 --> 00:18:56.190
that the problem
with the theorists

00:18:56.190 --> 00:18:57.430
is we talk way too long.

00:18:57.430 --> 00:18:59.100
But I'm going to
say one more thing

00:18:59.100 --> 00:19:02.510
and then I'll shut
up, which is I think,

00:19:02.510 --> 00:19:06.420
especially Americans,
particle physicists suffer

00:19:06.420 --> 00:19:08.540
from post-traumatic
stress disorder.

00:19:08.540 --> 00:19:14.050
Because in 1993, while building
the biggest experiment ever

00:19:14.050 --> 00:19:17.300
in Texas, a factor
of three times larger

00:19:17.300 --> 00:19:21.250
than the one in
Geneva, that Congress

00:19:21.250 --> 00:19:25.130
decided to cancel it
after spending $2 billion

00:19:25.130 --> 00:19:27.480
and digging 14 miles of tunnel.

00:19:27.480 --> 00:19:31.672
And that shook the field in
the United States to a degree

00:19:31.672 --> 00:19:33.880
where we stopped thinking
about physics all the time,

00:19:33.880 --> 00:19:36.565
and we started thinking a
little bit sociologically.

00:19:36.565 --> 00:19:38.250
Like, will they allow us?

00:19:38.250 --> 00:19:39.460
Can we keep going?

00:19:39.460 --> 00:19:42.770
Can we push in the direction
for pure knowledge,

00:19:42.770 --> 00:19:45.720
and pure science,
and basic research?

00:19:45.720 --> 00:19:48.560
There was a mistrust in the
people who, up to that point,

00:19:48.560 --> 00:19:50.600
were supporting
this kind of thing.

00:19:50.600 --> 00:19:57.890
And so that added to the drama,
especially before the machine

00:19:57.890 --> 00:20:02.090
turned on and a beautiful
discovery was made.

00:20:02.090 --> 00:20:05.970
NIMA ARKANI-HAMED:
So you should know

00:20:05.970 --> 00:20:09.530
that the Higgs is
a crazy particle.

00:20:09.530 --> 00:20:13.160
And it holds a really
enigmatic place

00:20:13.160 --> 00:20:16.550
in our understanding
of the world.

00:20:16.550 --> 00:20:19.950
On the one hand, it's
been, as you all know,

00:20:19.950 --> 00:20:24.030
it's been anticipated
for almost 50 years.

00:20:24.030 --> 00:20:27.211
Maybe you didn't know,
but it's been hypothesized

00:20:27.211 --> 00:20:29.210
and people have been
expecting something like it

00:20:29.210 --> 00:20:31.980
for a long time.

00:20:31.980 --> 00:20:35.660
So from the point of view
of a theoretical physicist,

00:20:35.660 --> 00:20:38.070
it's in the canon of
things which is allowed.

00:20:38.070 --> 00:20:40.180
We understand it very well.

00:20:40.180 --> 00:20:43.930
And it's the simplest
possible solution

00:20:43.930 --> 00:20:48.810
to a very fundamental
problem, which

00:20:48.810 --> 00:20:50.960
I won't explain now in detail.

00:20:50.960 --> 00:20:53.980
But anyway, it's the
simplest possible solution.

00:20:53.980 --> 00:20:55.910
On the other hand, it's
absolutely shocking

00:20:55.910 --> 00:20:58.810
that something so simple is
actually realized in nature.

00:20:58.810 --> 00:21:02.470
And I think that
shock is something

00:21:02.470 --> 00:21:06.650
which even us theorists-- I
mean we've known all of this

00:21:06.650 --> 00:21:12.480
in principle for a long
time-- but if you asked David

00:21:12.480 --> 00:21:14.410
many years ago when
he made that comment,

00:21:14.410 --> 00:21:18.930
I think it was commonplace
amongst theorists to think,

00:21:18.930 --> 00:21:20.800
well yeah, we know
the Higgs is there.

00:21:20.800 --> 00:21:23.162
It's about what's coming next.

00:21:23.162 --> 00:21:25.370
And I think something which
has happened to all of us

00:21:25.370 --> 00:21:31.290
in the interim, is as the actual
reality of this damn particle

00:21:31.290 --> 00:21:33.540
came into existence--
and, in fact,

00:21:33.540 --> 00:21:40.800
the particular strange mass that
it has also became evident--

00:21:40.800 --> 00:21:45.200
is we're all appreciating much
more deeply how utterly bizarre

00:21:45.200 --> 00:21:49.580
it actually is that something
so simple does describe nature.

00:21:49.580 --> 00:21:52.560
We've never seen anything
like it before anywhere.

00:21:52.560 --> 00:21:53.950
Anywhere in physics.

00:21:53.950 --> 00:21:58.270
There are all kinds
of different systems

00:21:58.270 --> 00:22:01.470
that people can engineer
in the laboratory that

00:22:01.470 --> 00:22:04.489
have qualitative
aspects of the physics

00:22:04.489 --> 00:22:07.030
very much like all the rest of
the particles, and the forces,

00:22:07.030 --> 00:22:11.360
and interactions that we're
familiar with in the vacuum

00:22:11.360 --> 00:22:12.450
of our universe.

00:22:12.450 --> 00:22:13.850
But never a Higgs.

00:22:13.850 --> 00:22:15.750
Never something that
looks like a Higgs.

00:22:15.750 --> 00:22:17.380
So the fact that,
on the one hand,

00:22:17.380 --> 00:22:19.500
the simplest possibility
is what's realized,

00:22:19.500 --> 00:22:21.499
but on the other hand,
that simplest possibility

00:22:21.499 --> 00:22:23.240
we've never seen
realized anywhere else,

00:22:23.240 --> 00:22:26.470
is absolutely bizarre.

00:22:26.470 --> 00:22:29.570
And I think we're all
appreciating how bizarre it is,

00:22:29.570 --> 00:22:32.210
and taking a step back.

00:22:32.210 --> 00:22:34.080
What's transpired
at the LHC so far

00:22:34.080 --> 00:22:36.957
is not exactly what
some of us expected.

00:22:36.957 --> 00:22:39.040
On the other hand, it's
not so different than what

00:22:39.040 --> 00:22:41.980
some others of us expected.

00:22:41.980 --> 00:22:46.680
And we're left in
a strange quandary.

00:22:46.680 --> 00:22:50.434
The idea that the experimental
high energy physicists,

00:22:50.434 --> 00:22:51.850
especially in this
country, suffer

00:22:51.850 --> 00:22:54.520
from the post-traumatic stress
disorder of the Superconducting

00:22:54.520 --> 00:22:56.980
Super Collider is
absolutely correct.

00:22:56.980 --> 00:23:00.460
And it's as David said, it
colored a lot how we even

00:23:00.460 --> 00:23:03.290
think about justifying
what we want to do.

00:23:03.290 --> 00:23:05.740
But in fact, the
real justification

00:23:05.740 --> 00:23:10.430
for doing what we're doing is
to keep pushing the frontier

00:23:10.430 --> 00:23:12.680
And seeing what's there.

00:23:12.680 --> 00:23:15.550
And in particular,
since we've never

00:23:15.550 --> 00:23:17.330
seen anything like
the Higgs before,

00:23:17.330 --> 00:23:20.420
it's very important to study
its properties in detail,

00:23:20.420 --> 00:23:21.890
and to go to even
higher energies,

00:23:21.890 --> 00:23:24.300
and see what its quantum
mechanical properties look

00:23:24.300 --> 00:23:24.450
like.

00:23:24.450 --> 00:23:26.660
And while that might be
difficult to convince people

00:23:26.660 --> 00:23:29.810
in this country to do it,
Europe is showing some ambition

00:23:29.810 --> 00:23:31.599
to do something like
this, and also China

00:23:31.599 --> 00:23:33.890
may be showing some ambition
to do something like this.

00:23:33.890 --> 00:23:35.750
Build the next accelerator.

00:23:35.750 --> 00:23:38.120
Three times bigger
than the LHC, even.

00:23:38.120 --> 00:23:39.940
In 20 or 30 years, this
is something people

00:23:39.940 --> 00:23:41.776
are starting to
take this seriously.

00:23:41.776 --> 00:23:44.110
MARK LEVINSON: Experimentalists
are chomping at the bit.

00:23:44.110 --> 00:23:45.692
FABIOLA GIANOTTI:
OK, so first of all,

00:23:45.692 --> 00:23:47.120
following on what
David said, you

00:23:47.120 --> 00:23:49.440
have perhaps picked
up another difference

00:23:49.440 --> 00:23:51.630
between theorists
and experimentalists.

00:23:51.630 --> 00:23:54.490
They work overnight,
we work on daytime.

00:23:54.490 --> 00:23:59.470
We sleep overnight so that
we are lucid on day time.

00:23:59.470 --> 00:24:06.330
Seriously, as an
experimentalist, first of all,

00:24:06.330 --> 00:24:08.240
we have just discovered
a new particle.

00:24:08.240 --> 00:24:09.590
It's a very special one.

00:24:09.590 --> 00:24:13.750
It's completely different from
the other elementary particles

00:24:13.750 --> 00:24:16.440
that we have observed until now.

00:24:16.440 --> 00:24:18.800
There were 16
elementary particles

00:24:18.800 --> 00:24:20.210
before the 4th of July.

00:24:20.210 --> 00:24:22.860
The Higgs boson is
the 17th particle.

00:24:22.860 --> 00:24:24.640
It's completely different
from the others.

00:24:24.640 --> 00:24:26.760
It's a very special
one for reasons

00:24:26.760 --> 00:24:28.455
that will be a bit
difficult to explain,

00:24:28.455 --> 00:24:30.380
a bit technical reasons.

00:24:30.380 --> 00:24:34.610
But I consider the Higgs
boson as a new friend.

00:24:34.610 --> 00:24:39.270
And as a new friend, you want
to know him, her, it, better.

00:24:39.270 --> 00:24:44.220
So we have to measure its
properties in more detail.

00:24:44.220 --> 00:24:48.040
For that we need more data, and
Mike will give us more data.

00:24:48.040 --> 00:24:49.182
Right?

00:24:49.182 --> 00:24:52.050
He said yes.

00:24:52.050 --> 00:24:55.410
So first of all, this is
really a very nice thing to do.

00:24:55.410 --> 00:24:58.695
To measure the Higgs boson
in all possible details,

00:24:58.695 --> 00:25:02.490
because it can be a
door to new physics.

00:25:02.490 --> 00:25:05.770
And into a better understanding,
also, of the universe,

00:25:05.770 --> 00:25:08.150
and many things that we
don't understand today.

00:25:08.150 --> 00:25:11.220
And the second thing
is that the LHC just

00:25:11.220 --> 00:25:14.170
started the exploration
of the new energy scale.

00:25:14.170 --> 00:25:16.920
We've been operating
at an energy which

00:25:16.920 --> 00:25:20.200
is a factor 1.7
lower than the design

00:25:20.200 --> 00:25:21.420
energy of the accelerator.

00:25:21.420 --> 00:25:26.140
So in one year from now, we will
get close to the design energy.

00:25:26.140 --> 00:25:29.410
And we have been
collecting an amount

00:25:29.410 --> 00:25:37.620
of data which is a factor of
10 less than the design value.

00:25:37.620 --> 00:25:39.330
And a factor of
100 less of what we

00:25:39.330 --> 00:25:42.150
can go by pushing the
machine to the extreme.

00:25:42.150 --> 00:25:44.370
To its extreme possibilities.

00:25:44.370 --> 00:25:45.740
So we're just starting.

00:25:45.740 --> 00:25:49.610
So for me, it's
like opening a door.

00:25:49.610 --> 00:25:51.400
And the expectation
is still very high

00:25:51.400 --> 00:25:54.110
to find new physics
in one year from now.

00:25:54.110 --> 00:25:58.510
It's like opening a door and
being in front of a nice garden

00:25:58.510 --> 00:25:59.900
with a lot of flowers.

00:25:59.900 --> 00:26:03.100
MARK LEVINSON: Mike,
you expressed concern.

00:26:03.100 --> 00:26:05.280
Are we ever going to
get this thing to work?

00:26:05.280 --> 00:26:08.050
You're responsible
for delivering beams

00:26:08.050 --> 00:26:09.880
to these people and
worrying about it

00:26:09.880 --> 00:26:11.930
damaging their detectors.

00:26:11.930 --> 00:26:13.860
Do you feel an ease now?

00:26:13.860 --> 00:26:16.415
The machine, for everybody
who hasn't seen the film

00:26:16.415 --> 00:26:19.500
and doesn't know, the
machine was turned off.

00:26:19.500 --> 00:26:21.800
They're doing major
renovations and upgrades.

00:26:21.800 --> 00:26:24.160
They will start again
at the end of next year

00:26:24.160 --> 00:26:26.910
at essentially
double the energy.

00:26:26.910 --> 00:26:29.450
And what's your
feeling now, Mike?

00:26:29.450 --> 00:26:32.230
Are you confident now that the
next one is going to go well?

00:26:32.230 --> 00:26:32.730
Easy?

00:26:37.120 --> 00:26:39.030
MIKE LAMONT: Yes.

00:26:39.030 --> 00:26:41.655
MARK LEVINSON: This
is for their benefits.

00:26:41.655 --> 00:26:42.780
MIKE LAMONT: We were lucky.

00:26:42.780 --> 00:26:47.070
I mean, the LHC was
initially conceived in '84.

00:26:47.070 --> 00:26:50.680
It took a long time to develop
the ideas, develop the magnets,

00:26:50.680 --> 00:26:53.180
the technology required.

00:26:53.180 --> 00:26:55.590
It was late, it was over budget.

00:26:55.590 --> 00:26:58.330
We turned it on,
and we blew it up.

00:26:58.330 --> 00:27:02.150
And we were off for over a
year picking up the pieces.

00:27:02.150 --> 00:27:06.650
So we started back
up at the end of 2009

00:27:06.650 --> 00:27:10.480
and we've just came about
halfway through a long shutdown

00:27:10.480 --> 00:27:14.410
of about two years to
consolidate the machine so we

00:27:14.410 --> 00:27:17.930
can take up to design energy
at the beginning of 2015.

00:27:17.930 --> 00:27:20.750
So I think it's fair to say an
awful lot of lessons have been

00:27:20.750 --> 00:27:25.150
learnt about the process,
about what went wrong,

00:27:25.150 --> 00:27:27.160
about the technology.

00:27:27.160 --> 00:27:29.980
And those lessons have been
applied during this shutdown.

00:27:29.980 --> 00:27:32.470
So I think the results
that are coming through

00:27:32.470 --> 00:27:36.590
give us some confidence that
we can go to 6 and 1/2 TeV

00:27:36.590 --> 00:27:38.107
without too many problems.

00:27:38.107 --> 00:27:40.190
MARK LEVINSON: I'm sure
they're all very comforted

00:27:40.190 --> 00:27:41.810
to hear that.

00:27:41.810 --> 00:27:45.990
So I want to actually look at
another side As David said,

00:27:45.990 --> 00:27:50.920
the film really shows the
human side of these characters.

00:27:50.920 --> 00:27:55.690
And I think you
already get a sense,

00:27:55.690 --> 00:27:59.107
they have more dimensions than
just what typically people

00:27:59.107 --> 00:28:00.190
think of us as physicists.

00:28:00.190 --> 00:28:01.710
And one of the
interesting things

00:28:01.710 --> 00:28:04.580
is that several of our
characters play the piano

00:28:04.580 --> 00:28:08.900
and talk about certain parallels
between art and physics.

00:28:08.900 --> 00:28:13.315
And I want to just show
the next clip, actually.

00:28:13.315 --> 00:28:14.976
