00:30:26.920 --> 00:30:32.050
that the creative
process the sciences

00:30:32.050 --> 00:30:36.010
and the arts must have
some similarities.

00:30:36.010 --> 00:30:44.930
One of the things they share is
that they appear that they are

00:30:44.930 --> 00:30:53.360
not very practical
endeavours to start with.

00:30:53.360 --> 00:30:55.970
They don't have an
obvious utilitarian value,

00:30:55.970 --> 00:30:59.280
either the arts or the
sciences, to start with.

00:30:59.280 --> 00:31:04.480
Yet they are very
important for human beings.

00:31:04.480 --> 00:31:07.740
And that, for example,
is a similarity

00:31:07.740 --> 00:31:10.580
that comes out that at
the very end of the movie.

00:31:10.580 --> 00:31:20.950
That they seem to be not needed
from the evolutionary point

00:31:20.950 --> 00:31:23.440
of view, yet they are there.

00:31:23.440 --> 00:31:28.100
And it's a mystery for
why we do art and science,

00:31:28.100 --> 00:31:31.230
and why we don't
satisfy ourselves

00:31:31.230 --> 00:31:33.080
from much more mundane
activities that

00:31:33.080 --> 00:31:35.165
are more directly
essential for our survival.

00:31:38.007 --> 00:31:39.840
MARK LEVINSON: Do you
want to say something?

00:31:39.840 --> 00:31:41.340
NIMA ARKANI-HAMED:
I mean, that this

00:31:41.340 --> 00:31:44.687
is a big subject about which
many platitudes are said,

00:31:44.687 --> 00:31:46.520
of the relationship
between art and science.

00:31:51.682 --> 00:31:53.390
I don't think it's
true for all the arts,

00:31:53.390 --> 00:31:55.223
but there are certain
parts of the arts that

00:31:55.223 --> 00:32:04.410
are extremely similar,
I think, psychologically

00:32:04.410 --> 00:32:06.814
to what we do in physics.

00:32:06.814 --> 00:32:08.980
Very particularly what we
do in theoretical physics.

00:32:08.980 --> 00:32:14.570
I think certain kinds of
novelists and composers

00:32:14.570 --> 00:32:16.320
go through a very
similar process

00:32:16.320 --> 00:32:17.680
we do as theoretical physicists.

00:32:20.200 --> 00:32:22.300
Because there's a
structure, and there

00:32:22.300 --> 00:32:25.970
is an external notion
of right and wrong.

00:32:25.970 --> 00:32:28.120
Now, of course we have
an external notion

00:32:28.120 --> 00:32:30.680
of right and wrong which is
almost literally God-given,

00:32:30.680 --> 00:32:33.640
out there in the universe.

00:32:33.640 --> 00:32:37.430
But really great music
and really great novels

00:32:37.430 --> 00:32:41.720
also have a sense that
there's some perfect structure

00:32:41.720 --> 00:32:45.160
that you constantly
fail to live up to.

00:32:45.160 --> 00:32:49.310
And you keep chipping away at
it until finally some jewel

00:32:49.310 --> 00:32:53.420
emerges, which was sitting there
all along, sort of inevitably

00:32:53.420 --> 00:32:54.520
there to be discovered.

00:32:57.670 --> 00:33:01.770
But which takes an enormous
amount of time and persistence

00:33:01.770 --> 00:33:03.780
to actually find.

00:33:03.780 --> 00:33:08.350
So I think that's a fundamental
psychological difference

00:33:08.350 --> 00:33:12.010
that-- I've talked
to Mark about this--

00:33:12.010 --> 00:33:16.190
I had a conversation with
Ian McEwan back in November

00:33:16.190 --> 00:33:17.450
at the London Science Museum.

00:33:17.450 --> 00:33:19.670
We had a wonderful
conversation, and had

00:33:19.670 --> 00:33:21.810
a very interesting
dinner afterwards.

00:33:21.810 --> 00:33:24.990
And it's very, very similar.

00:33:24.990 --> 00:33:27.890
The basic psychology
is very similar.

00:33:27.890 --> 00:33:31.310
As far as things like
playing the piano goes,

00:33:31.310 --> 00:33:33.860
I don't know how you
guys feel about it,

00:33:33.860 --> 00:33:38.680
but it's sort in the
opposite direction.

00:33:38.680 --> 00:33:42.240
And it's the difference between
playing and composition.

00:33:42.240 --> 00:33:44.350
I find that things
like playing the piano

00:33:44.350 --> 00:33:52.810
are a wonderful antidote to
the frustrations of research.

00:33:52.810 --> 00:33:57.940
The hardest part of our
job is that you wake up

00:33:57.940 --> 00:34:00.050
in the morning, and you
work very, very hard,

00:34:00.050 --> 00:34:02.860
and you have nothing to show
for it at the end of the day.

00:34:02.860 --> 00:34:07.910
And you fail miserably over
and over and over again.

00:34:07.910 --> 00:34:09.830
And we're not idiots.

00:34:09.830 --> 00:34:10.651
We're trying.

00:34:10.651 --> 00:34:12.400
We're trying this,
were trying that, we're

00:34:12.400 --> 00:34:13.590
trying the other thing.

00:34:13.590 --> 00:34:15.800
And maybe you take a
little bit of solace

00:34:15.800 --> 00:34:20.460
you failed a little less badly
today than you did yesterday.

00:34:20.460 --> 00:34:22.070
But mostly you fail.

00:34:22.070 --> 00:34:25.159
And every now and
then, if you're

00:34:25.159 --> 00:34:29.290
Savas it happens more often
than for some of the rest of us,

00:34:29.290 --> 00:34:30.679
you have a big peak.

00:34:30.679 --> 00:34:33.280
And you're maybe excited
for two or three days.

00:34:33.280 --> 00:34:34.139
And that's it.

00:34:34.139 --> 00:34:37.040
And then you're
back to the misery.

00:34:37.040 --> 00:34:39.070
So that's life.

00:34:39.070 --> 00:34:41.864
And that's what you have
to get used o if you

00:34:41.864 --> 00:34:43.030
want to be in this business.

00:34:43.030 --> 00:34:46.929
When Monica was complaining
about us drinking espresso

00:34:46.929 --> 00:34:49.310
and just chilling
all the time, it's

00:34:49.310 --> 00:34:53.250
hiding the suffering underneath.

00:34:53.250 --> 00:34:54.800
But playing the
piano, by contrast,

00:34:54.800 --> 00:34:59.661
is something that you
practice, you get better.

00:34:59.661 --> 00:35:00.410
And it feels good.

00:35:00.410 --> 00:35:03.626
It feels good because it's not
true for anything else we do.

00:35:03.626 --> 00:35:05.750
MARK LEVINSON: Actually,
that may be a nice lead-in

00:35:05.750 --> 00:35:10.720
to-- don't do the very next
