00:38:00.976 --> 00:38:03.250
and ask for more dollars to
be spent on your research,

00:38:03.250 --> 00:38:04.875
what should we say?

00:38:04.875 --> 00:38:07.000
NIMA ARKANI-HAMED: Can I
say something about that.?

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:10.410
So just so you have an idea
of the scale of the projects

00:38:10.410 --> 00:38:14.400
that we're talking about, when
we say big accelerators cost

00:38:14.400 --> 00:38:20.140
$10 billion, that's one part
in 10,000 of our GDP over 20

00:38:20.140 --> 00:38:22.580
years.

00:38:22.580 --> 00:38:25.390
So it's a lot on the scale
of scientific projects,

00:38:25.390 --> 00:38:31.450
but it's not back-breaking by
any stretch of the imagination.

00:38:31.450 --> 00:38:35.130
Now normally when this kind
of discussion comes up,

00:38:35.130 --> 00:38:41.590
we talk very appropriately about
the completely unanticipated

00:38:41.590 --> 00:38:46.520
consequences of
curiosity-driven basic research.

00:38:46.520 --> 00:38:49.240
Faraday, when he was famously
doing his experiments

00:38:49.240 --> 00:38:52.510
on electromagnetism, some
minister came to see him

00:38:52.510 --> 00:38:55.390
and asked exactly your
question, what is this good for.

00:38:55.390 --> 00:38:58.150
And he famously responded,
I don't know sir,

00:38:58.150 --> 00:39:00.570
but someday you will tax it.

00:39:00.570 --> 00:39:02.370
And that was correct.

00:39:02.370 --> 00:39:06.420
It was 20, 30 years before
people knew about radio waves.

00:39:06.420 --> 00:39:10.320
Our entire technological
life is driven by that.

00:39:10.320 --> 00:39:12.470
People in the 1930s
were doing experiments

00:39:12.470 --> 00:39:14.560
to try and understand
the detailed

00:39:14.560 --> 00:39:17.540
properties of the hydrogen atom,
and strange mysteries about how

00:39:17.540 --> 00:39:20.400
atoms can even work that led
to the development of quantum

00:39:20.400 --> 00:39:20.980
mechanics.

00:39:20.980 --> 00:39:24.850
Now quantum mechanics,
in the year 1927,

00:39:24.850 --> 00:39:27.877
was perhaps the most
esoteric branch of science.

00:39:27.877 --> 00:39:29.960
And relatively speaking,
the most esoteric branch,

00:39:29.960 --> 00:39:31.043
probably, we've ever seen.

00:39:31.043 --> 00:39:34.180
There were maybe six people on
the planet who understood it.

00:39:34.180 --> 00:39:36.470
And yet, no one could have
foreseen that 30 years

00:39:36.470 --> 00:39:39.770
after that our detailed
understanding of the quantum

00:39:39.770 --> 00:39:41.720
properties of matter
would lead to revolutions

00:39:41.720 --> 00:39:42.670
like the transistor.

00:39:42.670 --> 00:39:46.050
And again, by some
measures, 2/3 of our GDP

00:39:46.050 --> 00:39:49.627
is directly consequence
of quantum mechanics.

00:39:49.627 --> 00:39:50.710
So people talk about that.

00:39:50.710 --> 00:39:52.418
It's very appropriate
to talk about that.

00:39:52.418 --> 00:39:54.930
And that's the most
fundamental reason to do this.

00:39:54.930 --> 00:39:58.340
We push boundaries,
and particularly

00:39:58.340 --> 00:40:00.640
technological boundaries,
and in the process

00:40:00.640 --> 00:40:03.900
of doing that,
inevitably you have

00:40:03.900 --> 00:40:06.240
to bring so many people
together to solve

00:40:06.240 --> 00:40:09.020
such difficult problems,
especially technical problems,

00:40:09.020 --> 00:40:12.250
that great things are
bound to come from it.

00:40:12.250 --> 00:40:14.820
Again, famously the World Wide
Web was developed at CERN.

00:40:18.150 --> 00:40:19.900
Originally as a method
to allow physicists

00:40:19.900 --> 00:40:22.210
to share information
efficiently.

00:40:22.210 --> 00:40:23.650
And something
about scientists is

00:40:23.650 --> 00:40:25.650
that we don't care about money.

00:40:25.650 --> 00:40:28.082
I mean, it may be
strange, but we really

00:40:28.082 --> 00:40:29.040
don't care about money.

00:40:29.040 --> 00:40:31.770
Anything we discover,
as part of our culture,

00:40:31.770 --> 00:40:34.390
is something for the world.

00:40:34.390 --> 00:40:38.040
So all those things are true.

00:40:38.040 --> 00:40:41.130
If you want to be a super
hard-nosed, pragmatic,

00:40:41.130 --> 00:40:42.720
practical guy and
say, but come on,

00:40:42.720 --> 00:40:45.620
in actual, quantifiable
dollars and cents,

00:40:45.620 --> 00:40:49.030
what do I actually
get from investing

00:40:49.030 --> 00:40:51.320
in literally your accelerator?

00:40:51.320 --> 00:40:53.480
There was an interesting
study that was done.

00:40:53.480 --> 00:40:58.780
Not a study, but
sort of a half-study,

00:40:58.780 --> 00:41:00.770
but I think fairly
plausible, that was

00:41:00.770 --> 00:41:06.880
done about the impact of the big
accelerator we have in the US

00:41:06.880 --> 00:41:11.240
outside Chicago that was
ultimately shut down.

00:41:11.240 --> 00:41:15.375
That's the sad end of
US high energy physics.

00:41:15.375 --> 00:41:19.430
At least our leadership in
this particular frontier.

00:41:19.430 --> 00:41:25.410
That accelerator cost around
$5 billion over its lifetime.

00:41:25.410 --> 00:41:33.090
And if you actually
look at, concretely,

00:41:33.090 --> 00:41:37.220
the number of highly
trained PhD's,

00:41:37.220 --> 00:41:39.150
for example, that
were trained by this.

00:41:39.150 --> 00:41:41.130
The US Census Bureau
gives dollar figure

00:41:41.130 --> 00:41:42.400
to how much a PhD is worth.

00:41:42.400 --> 00:41:45.290
It's worth $2 million.

00:41:45.290 --> 00:41:47.870
So just the number of PhD's
that were trained already

00:41:47.870 --> 00:41:50.180
made up for the
$5 billion spent.

00:41:50.180 --> 00:41:57.620
And then on top of that, the
infrastructure that was there

00:41:57.620 --> 00:41:59.822
for developing
magnet technology,

00:41:59.822 --> 00:42:01.280
for developing
things that ended up

00:42:01.280 --> 00:42:04.740
being useful for cloud
computing and so on.

00:42:04.740 --> 00:42:07.650
And those industries would
have succeeded anyway,

00:42:07.650 --> 00:42:10.540
but even if you're very
conservative about just even

00:42:10.540 --> 00:42:12.450
a mild speed-up to the
development of those

00:42:12.450 --> 00:42:15.040
industries, you're
talking about $50 billion.

00:42:15.040 --> 00:42:18.460
It's a 10 to one return
on investment, easily.

00:42:18.460 --> 00:42:23.800
So by any measure, it's
one part in 10,000 of GDP,

00:42:23.800 --> 00:42:26.740
it's a 400-year
tradition of pushing

00:42:26.740 --> 00:42:29.000
the technical
boundaries of the world,

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:31.290
and giving a
template for how you

00:42:31.290 --> 00:42:33.760
go about solving seemingly
impossible problems.

00:42:33.760 --> 00:42:38.272
And even very directly, with
the technologies involved,

00:42:38.272 --> 00:42:40.600
a large return on investment.

00:42:40.600 --> 00:42:44.870
I think it's a no-brainer.

00:42:44.870 --> 00:42:47.777
But given that the
scale of money is large,

00:42:47.777 --> 00:42:49.360
this argument needs
to be made, and it

00:42:49.360 --> 00:42:50.510
needs to be made clearly.

